# Example environment for local runs and Docker Compose deployments.
#
# Copy to `.env` and edit. The real `.env` is gitignored: keep operator-specific
# values (host IPs, ports, provider tokens) here, never in tracked files.
#
#   cp .env.example .env
#
# `.agents/scripts/deploy.sh` loads this file explicitly (`docker compose
# --env-file`), so it belongs at the repo root. Running `docker compose` by hand
# with `-f docker/<file>` will NOT auto-load it (compose looks in the compose
# file's directory) — use deploy.sh, or pass `--env-file .env` yourself.

# --- Stack selection -------------------------------------------------------
# Which Docker Compose stack `deploy.sh` / active-compose-file.mjs target.
#   sqlite (or unset) -> docker/compose.yaml      (default, local dev)
#   postgres          -> docker/compose.pg.yaml   (the opt-in Postgres stack)
SYMPHONY_BOARD_ENV=sqlite

# Image tag for the prebuilt backend / web images (compose also builds locally).
# SYMPHONY_IMAGE_TAG=dev

# --- Postgres stack: web UI exposure ---------------------------------------
# Host interface the web UI binds to. Default is loopback-only (127.0.0.1):
# the UI is reachable only from the host itself. To let other devices connect,
# set this to ONE specific host interface — e.g. the host's Tailscale IP — so
# the surface stays scoped to that network. Never use 0.0.0.0.
#   SYMPHONY_PG_WEB_BIND=100.x.y.z      # e.g. `tailscale ip -4`
# SYMPHONY_PG_WEB_BIND=127.0.0.1

# Host port the web UI is published on (clients use http://<host>:<port>).
# SYMPHONY_PG_WEB_PORT=18080

# Postgres host port. Stays loopback-only by design — do NOT expose Postgres.
# SYMPHONY_PG_PORT=15432

# --- SQLite stack: web UI exposure -----------------------------------------
# The default (compose.yaml) web port is loopback-only too (it used to bind
# 0.0.0.0). Set SYMPHONY_WEB_BIND to ONE host interface to expose the UI to
# other devices (e.g. the host's Tailscale IP); never 0.0.0.0. Tailnet exposure
# is normally done on the host via `tailscale serve` to this loopback port.
# SYMPHONY_WEB_BIND=127.0.0.1
# SYMPHONY_WEB_PORT=8080

# --- Live event stream (webhook receiver) ----------------------------------
# The Live receiver is the only public-ingress service. It runs two listeners: a
# private reads listener (/api/live*) reached via the web sidecar, and a webhook
# listener (/webhooks/*) that is the ONLY surface intended for public HTTPS
# ingress. The loopback port below maps to the WEBHOOK listener; deployment
# ingress should target that port directly. The reads listener is never exposed
# publicly.
#
# Compose reads this interpolation from the .env in the PROJECT directory
# (docker/.env for `docker compose -f docker/compose.yaml`), NOT this repo-root
# file that board/api load via env_file — so set WEBHOOK_GITHUB_SECRET in
# docker/.env or the shell env for a direct run. Shared HMAC secret used to
# verify X-Hub-Signature-256 over the raw body; match the GitHub org webhook.
# WEBHOOK_GITHUB_SECRET=
# Previous secret, honored during a zero-downtime rotation window, then removed.
# WEBHOOK_GITHUB_SECRET_PREVIOUS=
#
# Host interface/port mapped to the webhook listener. Loopback-only; never
# 0.0.0.0. (compose.pg.yaml uses SYMPHONY_PG_LIVE_BIND / SYMPHONY_PG_LIVE_PORT,
# default 18091, to avoid colliding with this stack.)
# SYMPHONY_LIVE_BIND=127.0.0.1
# SYMPHONY_LIVE_PORT=18090
#
# Retention + scope (optional). Default TTL 30 days; row cap 50000. An optional
# comma-separated owner/repo allowlist drops out-of-scope org-webhook repos.
# LIVE_EVENT_TTL_DAYS=30
# LIVE_MAX_ROWS=50000
# LIVE_PROJECT_ALLOWLIST=sympoies/symphony-board
#
# Optional non-secret setup hint returned by GET /api/capabilities so thin
# clients can explain webhook setup. Deployment repos may set the public URL;
# this app repo deliberately ships it empty.
# LIVE_WEBHOOK_PUBLIC_URL=https://example.invalid/webhooks/github
# LIVE_WEBHOOK_PROVIDER=github
# LIVE_WEBHOOK_EVENTS=issues,pull_request,pull_request_review,issue_comment,push

# --- Provider tokens -------------------------------------------------------
# Read from the environment and referenced by name from config/sources*.json.
# Set the names your sources config actually references; values are secrets.
# GITHUB_TOKEN=
# GITLAB_TOKEN=
